FBIS4-64403 "drweu085__a94026" FBIS-WEU-94-085-A Daily Report 3 May 1994 ANNEX Italy & Vatican City Political Groups in Chamber, Senate Reviewed Political Groups in Chamber, Senate Reviewed BR2904113294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2015 GMT 28 Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY BR2904113294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database English BFN [Unattributed article: "Groups of at Least 20 in the House and Senate"] [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 28 -- With the decision taken today not to allow the creation of parliamentary groups of less than 20 deputies, the panorama of forces was divided into eight groups in the House and ten in the Senate and was arrayed in the parliament as follows: ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |At Montecitorio (Chamber of Deputies) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Group |Caucus Leader |Members | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Progressives |Luigi Berlinguer |143 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Northern League |Roberto Maroni |117 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Forza Italia |Raffaele Della Valle |113 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |National Alliance |Giuseppe Tatarella |109 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Mixed Group |Siegfried Brugger |49 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Communist Renewal |Famiano Crucianelli |39 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Popular Party |Beniamino Andreatta |33 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Christian Democratic Cen-|Clemente Mastella |27 | |ter | | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- The progressives are made up of 114 Left Democrat deputies, 11 Greens, nine from Network (Rete), six Social Christians, and three from Democratic Alliance. The Mixed Group is made up of 16 Socialists, 15 from Democratic Alliance, and 13 from Segni's Pact, plus three from the SVP [Suedtiroler Volkspartei], and one each from the UV [Valdaosta Union] and the Southern Action League. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |At Palazzo Madama (Senate) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Group |Caucus Leader |Members | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Progressives |Cesare Salvi |76 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Northern League |Francesco Speroni |60 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |National Alliance |Giulio Maceratini |48 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Forza Italia |Cesare Previti |36 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Popular Party |Nicola Mancino |34 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Mixed Group |Roland Riz |19 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Communist Renewal |Ersilia Salvato |18 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Rete-Greens |Edoardo Ronchi |13 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Christian Democratic Cen-|Massimo Palombi |12 | |ter | | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Socialists |Michele Sellitti |10 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- In the mixed group are seven life senators, six from Democratic Alliance, three from SVP and one each from UV, the Magris Slate and the Alpine League. Democratic Alliance, the Socialist Party and the Pact for Italy had all asked that smaller parliamentary groups be allowed to form but this request was turned down today by those representing the majority forces, sparking protests from members of the opposition. Socialist Gino Giugni, for one, said it was hard to understand the logic of a stance which forces the opposition into "an artificial compactness." As to the future, Giugni announced plans to forge a single group with Democratic Alliance, also in view of coming European elections. For Luciana Sbarbati, a Republican elected on the Democratic Alliance ticket, the majority, in refusing to allow the formation of smaller groups, was putting its worst foot forward, giving the impression of a bullying and vengeful rightwing "suspicious of any form of democratic pluralism."
